AB  - With the aim of using more environmentally benign chemical products and processes, a wide and global transition toward green and sustainable chemistry is required to solve sustainability issues from the production, use, and end of life of chemicals. We argue that for the effective development of a green and sustainable chemical industry, the integration of common visions toward sustainability (e.g., smaller, flexible chemical plants using renewable feedstock including waste, intensive dialog and cooperation with stakeholders, prevalence of product-service systems) along with the implementation of tailored policies built on the precautionary principle for supporting the emerging industries (e.g., tax exception, public procurement, etc) and withdrawing support for the traditional ones (e.g., redirecting R&D funding, carbon trading, etc.) are indispensable.
